Which Levels of Physiochemicals Effect Wine Type and Quality?

Rhedt Roelandt, Calvin Skalla, & Cory Skeers

5/7/2020

Introduction

Have you ever wondered what levels of physiochemicals will result in a high quality tasting wine? Do you know, just based off a few certain features, if a wine is red or white? Well, through this analysis, we will be demonstrating which chemicals have relationships with the quality of a wine and the key differences between red and white wines. Now, if you click below, we will explain the variables within the red and white wine datasets that were provided by UCI Machine Learning Repository.

Click to expand the variables and their descriptions

Variable Description
Sample Number Number given to each invdividual wine sample
Type Type of wine: 1 is white & 0 is red
Like Rating of wine: 1 is good & 0 is bad
Quality Rating score on the quality of wine
Fixed Acidity Amount of acid from the grapes
Volatile Acidity Amount of distillable acid in the wine
Citric Acid Amount of citric acid present to add flavor
Residual Sugar Leftover sugar from grapes after alcohol fermentation
Chlorides Amount of salt in the wine
Free Sulfur Dioxide Amount of \(SO_2\) not bound to other molecules
Total Sulfur Dioxide Portion of free \(SO_2\) plus the portion bounded to the other chemicals
Density Mass of dissolved solids
pH Measure of relative acidity vs.relative alkalinity of any liquid
Sulfites Amount of preservative (\(SO_2\)) for antioxidant and antibacterial properties
Alcohol Percent of alcohol content in the wine sample


The eleven numerical variables to differentiate the wines were given in grams per liter or per milliter, besides alcohol and density, which came in percentages. These variables, listed above, offer different levels of sweetness, bitterness, and acidity for the wines. Along with the variables we scraped, we created two additional columns for our analysis. When combining the red and white wine datasets, We mutated a type column to distinguish a 1 as a white wine and a 0 for a red wine. Then to interpret quality a little simpler, we created a binary like variable resulting in a 1 with quality greater than 5 and a 0 with quality less than or equal to 5.

The numerical variables were given in grams per liter or per milliter, besides alcohol and density, which came in percentages. Since the variables were given on different scales, for our analysis, we needed to use a method called min-max to create a dataset with normalized data. By using min-max normalization, we change our maximum observation in that column to a new value of 1 and the minimum of that column to a new value of 0. Then, for the rest of the values, calculate that difference between the value and the minimum divided by the difference between the maximum and minimum to receive all of your values on a [0,1] scale.

Visualizations to Gather Knowledge about the Variables


As seen form the scatterplots for each of the variables that have significant correlations with quality, there are positive correlations for alcohol and citric acid and negative correlations for density and volatile acidity.

Predicting Wine Quality

For predicting the quality of wines, we will use a Random Forest. When looking at the density plots of quality over red and white wines, we can perceive that there are more wines with a mediocre quality rating compared to wines with extreme quality ratings. Hence, we can assume that these wines are distributed normally. These distributions are also relatively equivalent between both types of wine.

Using a Random Forest method on a 90-10 split of train-test data, we attempt to classify a wines quality rating based on its physiochemical properties.

In addition to the low computational complexity in applying a fitted Random Forest model for future inference, the weighted importance rating for each variable is beneficial for interpretation.


As you can see, the variables determined through the Random Forest model selection to have great importance in predicting a wines quality match nicely with the variables with significant correlation. The relatively low importance rating for Type is to be expected as well, given the rough equivalence in the distributions of quality ratings for both white and red wines.


Prediction accuracy is relatively consistent in our training data.

And using the fitted model with our holdout test data

Overall, not bad! Around 70% overall accuracy, and fairly high overall focused on the diagonal, and relatively low (or 0) percentage predictions further out from the diagonal. Given the physiochemical makeup of a wine, our Random Forest classification model performs adequately in estimating the wines expected quality rating. Its greatest innaccuracies tend to fall around predicting quality ratings for mediocre wines rated between 5 and 7, while achieving perfect accuracy in testing when predicting the more extreme quality ratings of 4 and 8. In inference, this is likely desirable, as misclassifying these extremely high or low rated wines would be more costly than a slight misclassification of a mediocre wine (if, say, an investment opportunity were missed by mislabeling a high quality wine or, conversely, money were to be lost to a wine of inferior quality). In general, we are most interested in the extremes of wine qualities, at which our model performs very well.

Its relatively high performance in testing also provides support to the estimated importance of several of the variables, such as alcohol percentage, density, and volatilic acidity, in determining quality.

Predicting Wine Type

When pivoting to project which variables are significant in predicting the type of quality, we chose to use a few Logistic Regression models. Interestingly enough, from our results in predicting quality, the alcohol percentage was extremely important in correctly classifying a quality. However, looking at this violin plot distribution of alcohol percentage for white and red wines, we see rather similar distributions. So, first, we created a model based off the variables derived from a best subset selection. Then, we decided to produce a few singular variable logistic regression models for interpretability and visualizations.

For our model derived from a best subset selection, we ended up with the following variables to conduct the best analysis. Looking at the coefficent estimates and p-values, we can see that all eight of these variables are significant in predicting the type of wine for this model. Noticably, the p-value of density happened to be extremely low.

Wow! When running the full dataset through subset selection and then producing a logistic regression model, we were able to build a model with 99.8% accuracy. Inferring that given the levels of these eight values, we will be able to predict whether that wine is red or white with 99.8% confidence.

Now we will move onto the Singular Models

After running Type against each variable indpendently, we noticed three variables that are greatly significant in predicting wine type themselves. So, we created these three singular models with Type imposed onto total.sulfur.dioxide, chlorides, and volatile.acidity.


Type imposed onto total.sulfur.dioxide results in a 93% accuracy rating. Inferring that just knowing your wines level of total.sulfur.dioxide, you can predict your wines type approximately 93 out of 100 times.


Type imposed onto chlorides results in a 88% accuracy rating. Inferring that just knowing your wines level of chlorides, you can predict your wines type approximately 88 out of 100 times.


Type imposed onto volatile.acidity results in a 86% accuracy rating. Inferring that just knowing your wines level of chlorides, you can predict your wines type approximately 86 out of 100 times.
